Description: Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. The terminase large subunit acts as an ATP driven molecular motor necessary for viral DNA translocation into empty capsids and as an endonuclease that cuts the viral genome to initiate and to end a packaging reaction The terminase lies at a unique vertex of the procapsid and is composed of two subunits, a small terminase subunit involved in viral DNA recognition (packaging sequence), and a large terminase subunit possessing endonucleolytic and ATPase activities. Both terminase subunits heterooligomerize and are docked on the portal protein to form the packaging machine. The terminase large subunit exhibits endonuclease activity and cleaves the viral genome concatemer. Once the capsid is packaged with the DNA, the terminase complex is substituted by the tail. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Putative endonuclease. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Endonuclease responsible for the single-chain interruptions (nicks) located at specific positions in the minus strand of the viral genome. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Forms the portal vertex of the capsid and plays a role in governing correct capsid geometry (PubMed:26616586). This portal plays critical roles in capsid assembly, genome packaging, head completion protein attachment, and genome ejection (By similarity). The portal protein multimerizes as a single ring-shaped homododecamer arranged around a central channel (By similarity). Binds to the terminase subunits to form the packaging machine (By similarity). From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
FRD_BPT5 - Also known as B3-frd From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
Protein predicted: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 4. Probable tail fiber protein. From Escherichia phage Phieco32 (Escherichia coli phage phi32).

TYSY_SHESH - Protein inferred from homology: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 3. Catalyzes the reductive methylation of 2'-deoxyuridine-5'- monophosphate (dUMP) to 2'-deoxythymidine-5'-monophosphate (dTMP) while utilizing 5,10-methylenetetrahydrofolate (mTHF) as the methyl donor and reductant in the reaction, yielding dihydrofolate (DHF) as a by- product. This enzymatic reaction provides an intracellular de novo source of dTMP, an essential precursor for DNA biosynthesis. From Shewanella sediminis (strain HAW-EB3).

DECO_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Decoration protein that binds asymmetrically to the center of each capsid protein hexamer after capsid expansion. Stabilizes the capsid and protects from DNA release. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Serine protease involved in capsid assembly and maturation. Cleaves the major capsid protein, the decoration protein, the portal protein to yield mature procapsids competent for DNA packaging (Probable). Acts as a trigger for assembly of the capsid protein. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

CAPSD_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Major capsid protein that self-associates to form 120 hexamers and 11 pentamers, building the T=13 icosahedral capsid which about 860 Angstroms in diameter. Responsible for its self-assembly into a procapsid. The phage does not need to encode a separate scaffolfing protein because its capsid protein contains the delta domain that carries that function. The capsid gains its final stability through the reorganization of the subunits that takes place upon expansion. DNA encapsidation through the portal triggers capsid expansion and the binding of the decoration protein to the capsid exterior. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

DUT_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. This enzyme decreases the intracellular concentration of dUTP so that uracil cannot be incorporated into viral progeny DNA. This activity is sufficient to exclude uracil from the DNA during phage replication. In the case of dUTPase mutant phages, the host dUTPase activity is not sufficient to exclude uracil from T5 DNA and uracil are incorporated, leading to decreased phage viability. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
FEN_BPT5 - Also known as exo5 From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Protein predicted: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 4. Head completion protein that closes the capsid once the viral DNA has been packaged. Probably part of the head-tail connector by binding to the portal protein and to the tail completion protein. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
D14_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Stabilizes the tail sheath structure and acts as a connector between the end of tail and the portal vertex of the capsid. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

EXO2_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Possible exonuclease that may play a role in viral genome replication, DNA recombination, and host DNA degradation. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Plays an essential role in tail assembly by capping the rapidly polymerizing tail once it has reached its requisite length and serving as the interaction surface for the completion protein. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

TUBE_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Polymerizes to make up the central tail tube that is surrounded by the tail sheath protein (TSP). Tail tube protein polymerization takes place around the tape measure protein (TMP) and is probably directed by chaperone proteins. The tail is a stack of 40 trimeric rings of the TTP. Upon binding to host cell, the tail sheath contracts and the tail tube penetrates the host envelope. The tail tube is involved in viral genome delivery during ejection. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

EXO1_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Possible exonuclease involved in phage DNA recombination, replication, and repair. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Probable minor tail protein. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

SSDNA_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Required during DNA replication. Displaced viral DNA strands are transiently coated with the ssDNA-binding protein. It is then probably removed by the replisome that performs lagging strand synthesis or during the events that lead up to the recombination process. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
Accession: RF00005 - tRNA

TMP_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Fills the tail tube with its long coiled-coil domain and has pore-forming properties for host membrane penetration. Probable exolysin involved in host peptidoglycan digestion necessary for viral DNA entry into the host cell. Also functions as a tape measure protein that serves as a base for tail tube protein polymerization and acts as a template for tail length determination. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
Accession: RF00005 - tRNA
HEL10_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

TFLIV_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Endonuclease that introduces double-strand break into pseudo palindromic 17 bp DNA sequence yielding 1 bp extensions with 3'- overhangs. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Replicates the viral genomic DNA. This polymerase possesses two enzymatic activities: DNA synthesis (polymerase) and an exonucleolytic activity that degrades single-stranded DNA in the 3'-5' direction for proofreading purpose. The DNA synthesis very likely occurs by strand displacement. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
Protein predicted: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 4. From Escherichia phage Bf23 (Enterobacteria phage BF23).

A2_BPT5 - Also known as A2-3. Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Involved, together with A1 protein, in the second step transfer (SST) which allows the completion of viral DNA into the host cell. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

DIT_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Distal tail protein which forms a hexameric ring located at the tail tube end. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

A1_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Involved in the degradation of host DNA and the shutoff of host genes and phage pre-early genes. Together with A2 protein, involved in the second step transfer (SST) of viral DNA into the host cell, which leads to the complete entry of viral DNA into the host cell. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

BPPB3_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Probable baseplate hub protein. May also form a part of the central straight fiber at the tail tip. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

DMP_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Following host DNA degradation, is responsible for the degradation of 5'-dNMP's to deoxynucleosides that can be further excreted (PubMed:335083). Active on deoxynucleoside 5'-monophosphates but not active as a phosphatase on ribonucleotides, deoxynucleoside 5'- triphosphates, deoxynucleoside 3'-monophosphates, or deoxyoligonucleotides (PubMed:21305). From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

FIBC_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Probable central straight fiber at the tail tip. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

GRCA_ECOLI - Also known as yfiD. Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Acts as a radical domain for damaged PFL and possibly other radical proteins. From Escherichia coli (strain K12).

D5_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Putative transcription factor required for the expression of viral late genes. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Assembles together with pb1 to form the three L-shaped long tail fibers and probably the collar structure at the junction between the tail tube and the conical tail tip. Each fiber consists of a thin proximal rod of about 30 nm connected by a hinge to a thicker distal part of about 47 nm. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. The terminase small subunit binds to the packaging initiation site and regulates the ATPase activity of the terminase large subunit. The terminase lies at a unique vertex of the procapsid and is composed of two subunits, a small terminase subunit involved in viral DNA recognition (packaging sequence), and a large terminase subunit possessing endonucleolytic and ATPase activities. Both terminase subunits heterooligomerize and are docked on the portal protein to form the packaging machine. The terminase large subunit exhibits endonuclease activity and cleaves the viral genome concatemer at the long non-permuted direct terminal repeats. Once the capsid is packaged with the DNA, the terminase complex is substituted by neck proteins. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
bacteriophage T5 promoter for E. coli RNA polymerase, with embedded lac operator

DNMK_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Allows the synthesis of deoxyribonucleoside triphosphates necessary for the rapid viral DNA replication (PubMed:14711503). Phosphorylates all four dNMPs (PubMed:5846986). From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

OBP_BPT5 - Also known as D2. Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Displays bipolar ssDNA and dsDNA unwinding activities that require the same core catalytic residues for unwinding in either direction, the 3'-5' direction being more robust. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

HOLIN_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Accumulates harmlessly in the cytoplasmic membrane until it reaches a critical concentration that triggers the formation of micron- scale pores (holes) causing host cell membrane disruption and endolysin escape into the periplasmic space. Determines the precise timing of host cell lysis. Participates with the endolysin and spanin proteins in the sequential events which lead to the programmed host cell lysis releasing the mature viral particles from the host cell. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

ENLYS_BPT5 - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Endolysin with L-alanyl-D-glutamate peptidase activity that degrades host peptidoglycans and participates with the holin in the sequential events which lead to the programmed host cell lysis releasing the mature viral particles. Once the holin has permeabilized the host cell membrane, the endolysin can reach the periplasm and break down the peptidoglycan layer by hydrolyzing the link between L-alanine and D-glutamate residues. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).

PRP1_SALTY - Also known as prpA. Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Can hydrolyze phosphorylated Ser-, Thr- or Tyr-substrates in vitro. The natural substrate is unknown. From Salmonella typhimurium (strain LT2 / SGSC1412 / ATCC 700720).

NRDD_ECOLI - Experimental evidence at protein level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 1. Catalyzes the conversion of ribonucleotides into deoxyribonucleotides, which are required for DNA synthesis and repair. From Escherichia coli (strain K12).

Experimental evidence at transcript level: Swiss-Prot protein existence level 2. Assembles together with pb1 to form the three L-shaped long tail fibers and probably the collar structure at the junction between the tail tube and the conical tail tip. Each fiber consists of a thin proximal rod of about 30 nm connected by a hinge to a thicker distal part of about 47 nm. From Escherichia phage T5 (Enterobacteria phage T5).
